        "username": "thrush",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/45deac/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2025-10-09T22:42:22.914Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"desert_nip\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"72103\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/ccd318/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> desert_nip:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If you feel up to it, you could build an older version yourself and then uninstall the current one and replace it. Of course, this can cause issues as well, but if the current one seems unusable, that could be a good option.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Unfortunately, I’m not sure this would work. The reason I upgraded in the first place was that Signal refused to start, saying the database version was out of date, or something along those lines.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"LucasMZ\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"72103\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/lucasmz/48/55892_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> LucasMZ:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If Wayland is experimental in Mint, and not very reliable, then I could see that being an issue, though I would be more surprised that Signal running on X11 would be better, because that’s another layer of compatibility.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Ah, a good point. Yes, Wayland is definitely still experimental in Cinnamon. I had stopped using X11 because I was experiencing some unexplained UI crashing a couple of months ago that didn’t seem to happen under Wayland. I’m using the official installation method via command line for Signal, though.</p>\n<p>But that makes a lot of sense that Wayland could be the culprit. I didn’t realize Signal was displaying via Chromium. It’s certainly plausible that something changed with how Chromium rendering is handled that would explain the identical behavior in both Signal and Vivaldi. I’ll try falling back to X11.</p>",
