    "username": "LucasMZ",
    "name": "lucasmz",
    "excerpt": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"thrush\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"72103\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/45deac/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> thrush:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I’m running Linux Mint Cinnamon v22.2 in Wayland.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Isn’t this very much experimental?</p>\n<p>Are you using the unofficial Flatpak? Because, it can run Wayland and ended up defaulting to it effectively because of some recent Electron issues. If Wayland is experimental in Mint, and not very reliable, then I could see that being an issue, though I would be more surprised that Signal running on X11 would be better, because that’s another layer of compatibility.</p>\n<p>I wouldn’t be using Cinnamon with Wayland if I were you, it wasn’t stable enough last time I tried it. Either use X11, or go to KDE on Fedora, that was what I ended up doing for security purposes.</p>\n<p>Even NVIDIA should work well now a days if you’re using an up to date driver, I stopped using NVIDIA (which I was only using because I was borrowing a computer) some time after Explicit Sync started to become a thing, and at the end the experience was pretty OK, especially since I was avoiding using XWayland.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>had a nearly identical issue with Vivaldi a few days before</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hmmm, both of these are Chromium!</p>"
